messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

Summary: allow SIP calls for SIP contact entries and regular calls for regular entries

Problem Description:
For years users have been puzzled by the behavior of native SIP calling in Android to the point of abandoning the feature altogether.
If you have a SIP phone entry for a contact, you expect to use SIP calling for that number. Android will call that number using regular phone call instead.
The problem is Android will only consider "SIP number" a phone number in the format "sip:0123456789@sip.voipraider.com". But user also considers "SIP number" any number in the SIP field of the contact and wants to automatically select SIP call for that entry.

Fix Description:
This minimal change ensures that if the phone number is designated as SIP, it will not be changed back to regular TEL call just before calling (which happens since Android 4.x and doesn't make sense).

subject: Add com.nxp.mifare feature to Oppo Find 7 device

values.-1: Fails
values.+1: Verified

values.-1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Metrodroid author here, just chiming in with some context to help you with the decision to merge this patch.

"com.nxp.mifare" is part of the Android CDD[0], C-4-1 and C-4-2.  This isn't the only device (or Android distribution) to have this problem -- eg: Google's factory Pixel 2, 3 and 3A images _also_ have this bug.

I added a workaround to Metrodroid so that it will report that the OPPO Find7 supports MIFARE Classic (despite the platform saying otherwise).  For the purposes of Metrodroid, it is 100% cosmetic, but it is confusing to users, because it will mark certain transit cards as "unsupported" if they use MIFARE Classic.  I like to err on the side of false _negatives_, to underpromise and overdeliver.

MIFARE Classic Tool used to also do this check, but now does something a whole lot more complicated[1].  Metrodroid also used to do this[2], but I found it had many false positives and false negatives with some vendors and third-party AOSP distributions doing strange things like including _multiple_ (ie: unused) NFC drivers (eg: both NXP and Broadcom).

The problem arrives with some other Android software designed for working with MIFARE Classic cards (exclusively) marks the "com.nxp.mifare" feature as "required" in the application's manifest, under the expectation that device vendors will follow the CDD[0].  This unfortunately prevents these applications from being installed (via Play Store) on otherwise compatible hardware.

I'm very keen for there to be one less device and Android distribution with this error, so I've marking with "+1", on the basis that this would do what it says on the tin.  I don't have the device in question, nor have I tried to compile this, but it looks the same as what is on other devices.


[0]: https://source.android.com/compatibility/9/android-9-cdd.html#7_4_4_near-field_communications
[1]: https://github.com/ikarus23/MifareClassicTool/blob/da0a92182f5be295351d4e0038c204ed3536601a/Mifare%20Classic%20Tool/app/src/main/java/de/syss/MifareClassicTool/Common.java#L576-L655
[2]: https://github.com/micolous/metrodroid/commit/5c487da2034577e5e7300cd446fb5abfa374a7cf
